&gt; 
&gt; I typically use around 150, but set the target species to 5 using a
&gt; changing compatability threshold.  This gives a rough specie size of
&gt; 30. I read somewhere, and I can&#39;t remember where, some article about
&gt; Highland cattle having to have a breeding population of 30 to make the
&gt; gene pool viable.
&gt; 
&gt; I guess its also a trade off with time also.  I am evolving Torcs
&gt; controllers for Julain Togelius&#39; CIG 2008 commpetition.  Each
&gt; controller takes around 4 seconds to evaluate.  If I had a pop of over
&gt; 1000, it would take a long time for my poor laptop to finish each epoch.
&gt; 
&gt; Cheers
&gt; 
&gt; Matt
&gt; 
&gt; --- In neat@yahoogroups.com, Jeff Clune &lt;jclune@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Hello all-
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; What population sizes to you typically use for NEAT?
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; We have done experiments in the Avida digital evolution platform that
&gt;&gt; suggest that below 1,000 org drift starts to play a role. But a lot
&gt; of the
&gt;&gt; HyperNEAT papers use pop sizes of 150 or so. My guess is that the
&gt; diversity
&gt;&gt; preserving measure (&#39;speciation&#39;) and elitism help make smaller
&gt; populations
&gt;&gt; effective, but I was wondering if anyone has looked at the effects of
&gt;&gt; population size in NEAT in an effort to provide a *rough but general*
&gt;&gt; suggestion as to how big to make the populations in NEAT.
&gt;&gt; 
